Cell.Data: <-- The leftmost column 'Dialog' defines a new Dialog
Animation can either be an AG Signal (prefix with $) or an AG Action
If you want to play an Exact Positioned Animation add an additional ex_ prefix
LookAt target can be Actor1-Actor8. But Actor will only look at during the current line
If you want to have a sticky look at [constantly looking], prefix the target with $, e.g. $Actor2
Comment the Dialog: # Actors, Mood, Purpose
Let them look at each other
when a Sound is specified 'Delay' is relative to the end of the Sound and delays/brings forward the next line accordingly
if no sound is specified, Delay is relative to the beginning of the action and can only delay the next line
wait 1 second until Actor1 says 'Incoming Grenade'
When Playing an animation $ denotes a AG Signal, without an AG Action
A simple look at test, 2 generic Actors
when a Sound is specified 'Delay' is relative to the end of the Sound and delays/brings forward the next line accordingly
if no sound is specified, Delay is relative to the beginning of the action and can only delay the next line
wait for seconds until Actor1 says 'a3.wav'
A Facial expression test with just 1 actor. Works best on Morrison
make him talk look angry [fade in angry for 1 second]
Following needs 3 Actors. Actor1 turns to Actor2, salutes, turns to Actor3, salutes, and turns back to Actor1 and salutes again
Plays an exactly positioned animation signal 'Salute'. A direction is given in the look-at target
play an Exact Positioned Animation (EPA). The Direction is determined via the LookAt.
EPA need to be prefixed with 'ex_'. Then an AG Signal $ or an AG Action can be played
DialogScript to test sticky look-at. Actor1 will constantly try to look at Actor2 while playing the dialog
